summary: [Image description: A digital colour drawing of two fake Pokemon that I created that are based on European wolves. The images of...
caption:
[Image description: A digital colour drawing of two fake Pokemon that I created that are based on European wolves. The images of the Pokemon are placed against stylised Pokeball graphics and each has a blue text box with relevant information next to them. This information is replicated in the artist’s comment below. The first Pokemon is Pupsicle, a small blue puppy with a dark back, ice around its eyes, icicle teeth, white fluffy collar, tail tip and paws and white dot markings that look like falling snow. It is standing and looking up. The second Pokemon is Lupice, an adult wolf with the same coat pattern as Pupsicle but darker and with a jagged collar, tail tip and paws and icicles growing from its eyes, ears, nose, mouth and belly. It is sitting on a patch of ice and breathing out icy mist.]

#71 Pupsicle (Pup + Popsicle)
Icicle Pokemon
Ice

Despite its adorable appearance, this puppy is brave enough to run through blizzards to rescue lost travellers.

#72 Lupice (Lupus + Ice)
Icicle Pokemon
Ice

These Pokemon used to guard mountain temples against thieves seeking the holy texts within.

Evolution:

Pupsicle -(lvl 30)- Lupice

These guys are based on Eurasian wolves, a species that used to exist in Britain until they were deliberately wiped out, but are slowly being reintroduced. Their behaviour is modelled on rescue dogs like St. Bernards and the temples they guard are based on Tibetan temples. Not very British, but because I think the idea of mystic wolves guarding temples and rescuing travellers is cool.

Font is ‘Power Red and Blue’.

Photoshop CS4

blog.name: pokegodsandmissingno
blog.title: P̵o̵K̸é̴G̸o̸D̷s̸ and Frightful Things to Come?
blog.description: There is a growing desire and expectation of humans here on Earth in making full contact with PoKéMoN who are still unknown. Back in 1995, when I saw my first UPM (Unindexed Pocket Monster), I found out very quickly that other people thought you were totally crazy if you said you saw such things. The world has changed quite a bit since then when I was a child. In fact, in late 1997, a poll taken in Kanto shows that for the first time ever, more than fifty percent of residents now believe in PokéGODS's. Since then, there have been polls that put the figure at over eighty percent or more.
